- Length: 150-250 words
- Reference specific details from the deal content
- Build on previous communications (never repeat same talking points)
- Address ALL relevant attendees from the most recent call or meeting (infer from deal content and RAG context — use a group salutation like 'Travis and Uday,' if multiple people attended)
- End with a clear, specific next step or call to action
- Sign off as: Austin Holland | Clearwater Security & Compliance`,

  pre_call_planner: `Create a comprehensive PRE-CALL PLANNER for Austin Holland preparing for an upcoming meeting with ${ctx.company_name}.
Include these sections:
## MEETING OBJECTIVE
## KEY ATTENDEES & ROLES
## DEAL STATUS (P2V2C2 Summary)
## PAIN POINTS TO REFERENCE
## CPS TALKING POINTS (aligned to current stage: ${deal.critical_activity_stage || deal.deal_stage || 'discover'})
## OPEN QUESTIONS TO ASK
## ANTICIPATED OBJECTIONS & RESPONSES
## DESIRED OUTCOMES FROM THIS MEETING
## NEXT STEPS TO PROPOSE
Be specific. Use names. Reference actual deal evidence.`,

  internal_team_update: `Write an INTERNAL TEAM UPDATE for the ${ctx.company_name} deal.
Format: Exactly TWO paragraphs of narrative prose. NO bullets. NO section headers.
Paragraph 1: Current state — where it came from, client situation, key players, pain, PE/board dynamics. Analytical, specific.
Paragraph 2: Strategic trajectory — what Clearwater must do, urgency, winning strategy. Forward-looking, inferential, dry wit.
Tone reference: Astute, eloquent, professional with subtle sarcasm about corporate behaviors or client indecision.`,

